  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Boosting Meki Batu&apos;s vegetable sales</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Meki Batu is a primary cooperative union with 7994 members (18% - 1414 female) and 141 member primary cooperative organisations. Most of the farmers farm next to the Ziway, a natural lake, and have irrigation access from the lake and are engaged mainly in vegetable production. Meki Batu members are strong in production of maize seed, and provide up to 40% of the maize seed requirements in the Oromia Region. The largest income earner for the union is the distribution of fertilizers. Meki Batu union members largest concern is the lack of marketing ability of the union for their predominant products which is vegetables including onions, tomatoes, green pepper, green beans, cabbage and papaya. Farmers sell their crops predominantly to local traders who market the products to the surrounding cities, including Addis Ababa.

Meki Batu union and members have very little knowledge and understanding on pricing and marketing requirements and therefore accept below market returns. An independent market supply chain analysis was conducted by agripoolers from the Netherlands (Jacco Vooijs and Willem Rodenberg) in December 2012, and therefore this action plan aims to use this report to strengthen the union in vegetable marketing. This includes revising their obsolete 5 year strategic business plan to align more with the members vegetable marketing ambitions and sourcing finance through loans from the banks to support the plan. Some of the main challenges to be addressed is improve the overall marketing and logistics management of vegetable marketing (supply/farmer production &amp; market demand). Have a better understanding of the market requirements and prices and improve and strengthen their relationship with the top performing PC&#x2019;s to sustain a good supply base and build market clients. The Meki Batu financial management system is currently manual, and this hinders decision making process and therefore computerizing the accounting system and preparing for a Management Information System (MIS) is an important requirement. One of the main challenges of the farmers is their high dependence on irrigation pumps to pump water into the irrigation furrows. There are many models of pumps, and there is a lack of qualified maintenance or spare part availability.  To address this issue the union is planning a survey to understand which pumps are preferred by the farmers and support the more popular brands with maintenance and spares.

-	To improve the supply chain and purchase logistics and management
-	To improve the output marketing performance
-	To develop a strategic business plan including an outline of the finance need for the coming years.</narrative>
  </description>
